nof the systematic uncertainties and their correlations. The mass value\ndetermined is $173.18 \\pm 0.56 \\thinspace ({\\rm stat}) \\pm 0.75 \\thinspace\n({\\rm syst})$ GeV or $173.18 \\pm 0.94$ GeV, which has a precision of $\\pm\n0.54%$, making this the most precise determination of the top quark mass.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Jul 2012 18:09:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 11 Jul 2012 00:31:41 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 11 Sep 2012 19:16:18 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 16 Nov 2012 21:34:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-05"}
{"id":"1207.1070","submitter":"Arnab Kumar Ray","authors":"Sourav Sen and Arnab K. Ray","title":"Implications of nonlinearity for spherically symmetric accretion","comments":"14 pages, ReVTeX. Substantially revised with respect to the previous\n  version. Three figures and a new section (Sec. VI) added","journal-ref":"Physical Review D, 89, 063004, 2014","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.89.063004","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We subject the steady solutions of a spherically symmetric accretion flow to\na time-dependent radial perturbation. The equation of the perturbation includes\nnonlinearity up to any arbitrary order, and bears a form that is very similar\nto the metric equation of an analogue acoustic black hole. Casting the\nperturbation as a standing wave on subsonic solutions, and maintaining\nnonlinearity in it up to the second order, we get the time-dependence of the\nperturbation in the form of a Li\\'enard system. A dynamical systems analysis of\nthe Li\\'enard system reveals a saddle point in real time, with the implication\nthat instabilities will develop in the accreting system when the perturbation\nis extended into the nonlinear regime. The instability of initial subsonic\nstates also adversely affects the temporal evolution of the flow towards a\nfinal and stable transonic state.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Jul 2012 18:10:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 25 Sep 2012 02:07:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 12 Apr 2014 18:23:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-05"}
